8/8

Buy #Bitcoin.

Secure your monetary energy.

7/8

There will only ever be 21M #Bitcoin.

The monetary energy stored in the Bitcoin you own will never leak over time. One satoshi will always be (1/1M)/ 21M of the Bitcoin network.

You can send Bitcoin with minimal fees, that reward the miners that secure the network.

6/8

Real Estate.

You can't put a house in the Hamptons on a boat and ship it to Europe, it will lose its monetary value and its not fungible.

Closing costs + yearly property taxes result in a loss of monetary energy across time.

5/8

Gold loses its energy across time by becoming commoditized. The mining industry has become oversaturated/subsidized, resulting in an industry that operates irrationally; running where variable MC>MB.

Through space, watch @obxonnetflix. Any energy lost?

4/8

The dollars loses its energy across time by means of inflation.

And across space by high bank transaction fees.

3/8

Outside of Bitcoin, every other SOV asset class fails to transfer energy across time and across space.

2/8

Money is human's highest form of energy.

The ability to channel chemical, kinetic and gravitational energy is what has set humans apart from other species.

In an economic setting, humans quantify the energy they have channeled by assigning it monetary value.

1/8

45% of Americans don't have equity exposure.

They missed out on a 33% gain this year. And an 881% gain since 1993.

What companies are working to fix this?

The lack of financial literacy and not knowing that our government will NOT allow the broader equity market to decline, deters Americans from investing.

They read the "market crash" headlines and associate stocks with gambling.

The result: massive wealth inequality.

For those who aren't high income earners, or have little to no capital to deploy, it is these decisions that ultimately determine their wealth.

For middle/lower class, increases in wealth improve quality of life exponentially more than upper class. 

~Convex utility function~

No one calculates the opportunity cost of the price increase, had that money been used to buy index funds.

Why would they?

Seems like a crazy way to determine your willingness to pay.

But, that's the issue.

The marginal increases in the costs of goods fails to go completely unnoticed, but it's usually not enough to change one's mind, especially on smaller ticketed and essential items.

With stagnant wages, non-equity owning Americans get poorer every day.

"Damn, $50.00 to fill up my tank. Must be the new President!"

"$3.00 for a Dunkin' Iced? You've got to be kidding me!"

I hear it all the time, but why doesn't anybody do anything?

According to Forbes, only 55% of Americans own equities.

June CPI: 5.4%

$SPY 12 Month Return: 33%

Market manipulation by the Fed is annihilating the middle class, most don't see it.

It's hidden in opportunity cost and they have no idea.
